class Solution:
    def countPairs(self, root: TreeNode, target: str) -> int:
        # get the number of possible sub-sequences
        def dfs(node, sub_sequence, i):
            if node is None:
                return
            if len(sub_sequence) == 0:
                return
            if len(sub_sequence) == 1:
                # if this is the target sub-sequence, add it to the answer
                if sub_sequence[0] == target:
                    answer[i] += 1
                return
            # if this is not, it's a sub-sequence that is already visited, skip this and move on to the next sub-sequence
            if sub_sequence[0]!= target:
                return
            # perform DFS on all the sub-sequences
            dfs(node.left, sub_sequence[1:], i + 1)
            dfs(node.right, sub_sequence[1:], i + 1)
            # add the number of sub-sequences from this visit into the answer
            answer[i] += sub_sequence[0] * sub_sequence[0]

        answer = [0] * len(target)
        # set root as the root of the given substring, this is done in order to avoid duplicates
        root = TreeNode(root)
        # set the first sub-sequence as the root
        dfs(root, [target], 0)
        return answer[0]
